At steady-state velocity, when the modeled current goes to 0, the Talon sim stator current goes to negative 15A and the supply current goes to negative 13A.

In the 2025 API, the Talon FX simulation layer assumes a Kraken X60 with FOC. Switching to DCMotorSim.getKrakenX60Foc(1) fixes this issue and partially closes the error on the other one.

The current from the DCMotorSim physics model is not close to the stator current from the Talon during spin-up. The model current (green line) hovers around 70A rather than the Talon limit in the 110-120A range.

This one is a bit more interesting and appears to be related to DCMotorSim only running at 50 Hz instead of something closer to 1 kHz. Our simulated current measurements are currently based on the instantaneous current given the simulated duty cycle and the current rotor velocity, updated at 1 kHz. I suspect this is a discretization issue between that and DCMotorSim. I believe DCMotorSim assumes the motor’s back emf exponentially decays towards the supplied motor voltage for the 20 ms update, when in the case of current limiting the applied motor voltage is constantly moving along with back emf.

If you put our simulation code into a Notifier (as we do in our swerve projects), you’ll notice that the rest of the error goes away as you speed it up. 500 Hz appears to be sufficient to eliminate the error. Increasing the MOI further (such as all the way to 0.2 kg m²) also fixes the issue at the original 50 Hz.

private final double updateIntervalSec = 0.002; // 500 Hz
private Notifier m_simNotifier = null;

@Override
public void simulationInit() {
    /* replaces simulationPeriodic() */
    if (m_simNotifier == null) {
        m_simNotifier = new Notifier(() -> {
            batteryVoltageVolts = RobotController.getBatteryVoltage();
            leaderSim.setSupplyVoltage(batteryVoltageVolts);

            leaderSimVoltageVolts = leaderSim.getMotorVoltage();
            leaderSimSupplyCurrentAmps = leaderSim.getSupplyCurrent();
            leaderSimTorqueCurrentAmps = leaderSim.getTorqueCurrent();

            wheelSim.setInputVoltage(leaderSimVoltageVolts);
            wheelSim.update(updateIntervalSec);

            modelWheelPositionRot = wheelSim.getAngularPositionRotations();
            modelWheelVelocityRPS = wheelSim.getAngularVelocity().in(RotationsPerSecond);
            modelWheelAccelRadPerSecSq = wheelSim.getAngularAccelerationRadPerSecSq();
            modelCurrentAmps = wheelSim.getCurrentDrawAmps();

            leaderSim.setRawRotorPosition(modelWheelPositionRot * gearReduction);
            leaderSim.setRotorVelocity(modelWheelVelocityRPS * gearReduction);
        });
        m_simNotifier.startPeriodic(updateIntervalSec);
    }
}
